# Engineering standards

- Prefer **generalized fixes** over local patches; fix the **canonical layer** (normalization, mapping, planning, validation, compilation), not only the symptom.
- **Single source of truth** once structured intent or canonical data exists; do not parse the same concept in multiple places.
- Keep **business logic out of** controllers, transport handlers, and thin UI layers.
- **Avoid monolithic files**; extract domain logic into focused modules.
- Prefer **pure, composable, typed** functions where practical.
- **Limit regex** to narrow parsing; do not build core architecture on regex.
- If **more than two** similar conditionals are needed, stop and refactor.
- Make retries, setup, migrations, reconciliation, and upserts **idempotent** where practical.
- **Validate** generated SQL, code, or commands before execution.
- **Fail clearly**; do not hide errors to keep tests green.
- Comment **invariants and tradeoffs** when complexity is unavoidable.

## Anti-patterns (do not)

- Add “one more regex” for one more prompt, or another fallback because the main path is weak.
- Special-case production logic for a single test.
- Keep growing giant utility/controller files.
- Let passing tests replace architectural review.
- Silently reinterpret structured intent after it has been normalized.
